\par \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 Now, last week we were looking at some Greek ideas about goodness. And we discussed Plato's idea about virtue and how to lead a good life. But today I want to start look\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
ing at a more modern idea about what goodness is. Specifically, I want to look at the theory known as utilitarianism.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 Some students here are probably familiar with this theory from previous courses, but it might be useful for you to think about it again. \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
OK. Essentially what utilitarians, that is, the philosophers who represent this line of thought, what they argue - is that the goal of human conduct is happiness. Therefore, they say that an action which tends to lead to happiness is a good one and that a
\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 n\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
 action that tends to lead to unhappiness is a bad one. This means the happiness not just of the person doing the action but the happiness of everyone affected. So, this theory contradicts theories of ethics, which argue that an action is made wrong or ri
\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 g\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
ht because of the reason or motive of the person doing the action. The motive is not the important thing for utilitarians. In fact, some of these philosophers claim that it's possible for a good thing to be done for a bad motive and also the opposite - a 
\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 b\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 ad thing can be done for a good reason. The important thing for them is whether or not the action promotes happiness or unhappiness.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 So, we agree then that acts have consequences - some good consequences, some bad, and some, perhaps, neither. But how does\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
 a person measure what makes happiness? Well, according to the most famous utilitarian, the philosopher John Stuart Mill, happiness is caused by pleasure and unhappiness is caused by pain. Mill and others argued that only pleasure and pain have value in t
\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 h\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
emselves and that happiness is a result of the amount of pleasure versus pain a person receives. They also say that we can compare the amount of pleasure or pain produced by alternative actions and decide which has better consequences.
\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 OK, so that's the t\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
heory in a nutshell. Of course, many thinkers have criticized it. For example, what do we say about an action that's considered wrong if on a particular occasion it leads to more happiness than the reverse? There may be occasions, for example, when tellin
