\par 
\par \hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
Now, other critics have pointed out that the value of life is more than just a balance of pleasure over pain. But, in fact, Mill's form of the theory did allow for differences in kinds of pleasures. Some pleasures he said were preferable to others. For
\hich\af2\dbch\af12\loch\f2 
 example, intellectual pleasures, Mill said, were superior to mere physical ones. However, in making this distinction, it's been argued that he fell into a kind of trap. If there are different qualities of pleasure, then how do we judge which qualities ar
